{{Infobox monarch | name = Abu 'Ali Chaghani | title = Ruler of [[Chaghaniyan]] | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | succession = | reign = 939–955 | predecessor = [[Abu Bakr Muhammad]] | successor = [[Abu'l Muzaffar ibn Muhammad]] | spouse = | spouse-type = | issue = | full name = | house = | dynasty = [[Muhtajids]] | father = [[Abu Bakr Muhammad]] | mother = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = 955 | death_place = [[Rey, Iran|Ray]] | religion = [[Sunni Islam]] }} '''Abu 'Ali Ahmad Chaghani''' ({{lang-fa|ابوعلی احمد چغانی}}) (died 955) was the [[Muhtajids|Muhtajid]] ruler of [[Chaghaniyan]] (939&ndash;955) and governor of [[Samanid]] [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]] (939&ndash;945, 952&ndash;953). He was the son of [[Abu Bakr Muhammad]].
== Biography == In 939, Muhammad became ill and Abu 'Ali was assigned to succeed him in his posts. As governor of Khurasan he undertook several campaigns in northern [[Iran]], conquering [[Gurgan]] and territory as far west as [[Ray, Iran|Ray]] from the [[Ziyarids]], forcing the Ziyarids to acknowledge Samanid authority, and killing the [[Dailamite]] adventurer [[Makan ibn Kaki]]. After he departed for Khurasan the [[Buyid]] [[Rukn al-Dawla]] seized Ray. In 945 Abu 'Ali returned and expelled the Buyids from Ray, but they returned a year later. [[File:Iran circa 1000AD.png|thumb|right|250px|Persia in the mid-10th century]] That same year, 945, the Samanid amir [[Nuh I]] dismissed Abu 'Ali from the governorship of Khurasan after hearing complaints of the latter's harsh rule,{{sfn|Frye|1975|pp=149-151}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1984|pp=764–766}} and sought to replace him with a Turk, the [[Simjurids|Simjurid]] [[Ibrahim ibn Simjur]]. Abu 'Ali refused to accept his dismissal and rebelled. He was joined by several prominent Iranian figures such as [[Abu Mansur Muhammad]], whom he appointed as the commander of Khurasan. Abu 'Ali also convinced a Samanid, Nuh's uncle [[Ibrahim ibn Ahmad]], to come from [[Iraq]] and installed him as amir in [[Bukhara]] when he took the city in 947. Abu 'Ali, now having secured his position, returned to Chaghaniyan. Ibrahim, however, was unpopular with the people of Bukhara, and Nuh soon retaliated by retaking the city and blinding Ibrahim and two brothers.
When the news of the re-capture of Bukhara arrived to Abu 'Ali, he once again marched towards Bukhara, but was defeated by an army sent by Nuh and withdrew back to Chaghaniyan. After some time, he left the region and tried to obtain support from other Samanid vassals. Meanwhile, Nuh had Chaghaniyan ravaged{{sfn|Bosworth|2011|p=63}} and its capital sacked.{{sfn|Frye|1975|pp=149-151}} Another battle shortly ensured between Abu 'Ali and a Samanid army in [[Tukharistan]], which resulted in a Samanid victory. Fortunately for Abu 'Ali, he managed to secure the support of other Samanid vassals, such as the rulers of [[Khuttal]], and the Kumiji mountain people, and in the end made peace with Nuh, who allowed him to keep Chaghaniyan in return for sending his son [[Abu'l Muzaffar Abdallah]] as hostage to Bukhara.{{sfn|Bosworth|2011|p=63}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1984|pp=764–766}}
Some time later, Abu 'Ali was sent on an expedition to quell a rebellion near Chaghaniyan under a self-proclaimed prophet known as Mahdi.{{sfn|Bosworth|2011|p=64}} Abu 'Ali managed to successfully defeat and capture the latter and then had his head sent to Bukhara. In ca. 951/2, Abu 'Ali's son Abu'l Muzaffar Abdallah died in an accident{{sfn|Bosworth|1984|pp=764–766}} and his corpse was shortly sent to Chaghaniyan, where he was buried.{{sfn|Bosworth|2011|p=64}}
In 952 following the death of the governor of Khurasan, [[Mansur ibn Qara-Tegin]] (Ibrahim ibn Simjur had already died in 948), 'Abu Ali was reinstated by Nuh as governor of the province.{{sfn|Frye|1975|pp=149-151}} At the insistence of the Ziyarids he began a war with the Buyid Rukn al-Dawla, but was unable to take Ray and made peace. This action upset Nuh, who again removed him from the governorship. 'Abu Ali fled to the Buyids and received an investiture diploma for Khurasan from the [[Caliph]] and was even reinforced by an army under [[Lashkarwarz]], but was unable to enforce his claim or even return to Chaghaniyan.
In 955 he and one of his sons died of the plague in Ray. Their bodies were shortly brought to Chaghanian where they were buried. A certain Muhtajid prince, [[Abu'l Muzaffar ibn Muhammad]], probably the grandson of 'Abu Ali, was then appointed as the new ruler of Chaghaniyan. However, according to some other sources, Abu 'Ali was succeeded by his relative [[Abu'l-Hasan Taher]].{{sfn|Bosworth|1984|pp=764–766}}
