{{Infobox recurring event | name = Bayfield Applefest | logo = | image = | imagesize = | caption = | date = | begins = | ends = | frequency = Annual | location = [[Bayfield, Wisconsin|Bayfield]], [[Wisconsin]], [[United States]] | years_active = {{Age in years|1962}} | first = | last = | prev = | next = | participants = | attendance = 60,000 (estimated) | organised = | website = {{Official website|https://www.bayfield.org/festivals-events/bayfield-apple-festival/}} | footnotes = }}
[[File:BayfieldWI-039-050507.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Downtown Bayfield]] The '''Bayfield Applefest''' is a fall [[harvest festival]] held in October, in [[Bayfield, Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bayfield.org|url=https://www.bayfield.org/festivals-events/bayfield-apple-festival/|accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> Founded in 1962, it has become a destination for many people from across the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]], with an annual attendance of approximately 60,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|title=Duluth News Tribune|url=http://www.duluthnewstribune.com/lifestyle/3582660-apple-time-theres-lots-slices-bayfields-annual-event|accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref>
The festival is a celebration of Bayfield's local heritage, especially showcasing products from the many local [[Orchard|apple orchards]] and [[Winery|wineries]]. The festival offers a variety of events and attractions. The street festival features over 60 booths, offering fresh foods and local crafts. Other attractions include tours of the 14 local orchards, live music, and an [[amusement park]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Duluth News Tribune|url=http://www.duluthnewstribune.com/lifestyle/3582660-apple-time-theres-lots-slices-bayfields-annual-event|accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref>
==History== In the early 1960s, Jim Erickson, the owner of an orchard in Bayfield, was traveling to North Dakota to deliver a shipment of apples. While in [[Duluth, Minnesota|Duluth]], his truck had a flat tire. While waiting for a spare to be driven up from home, many people stopped to ask about buying his fruit. After selling bushels of apples to 25 people, he started wondering why he (and other Bayfield apple growers) were traveling so far to sell their goods. Realizing an opportunity, a discussion was raised about selling the local orchard's products more locally, and the idea of Applefest was born. The attendance of the first event in 1962 was 5,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Duluth News Tribune|url=http://www.duluthnewstribune.com/lifestyle/3582660-apple-time-theres-lots-slices-bayfields-annual-event|accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> Over they years, Applefest has continued to experience huge growth in attendance.
==In popular culture== *Honored as the “Best Festival in Wisconsin” by [[Wisconsin Trails|Wisconsin Trails Magazine]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Travel Wisconsin|url=https://www.travelwisconsin.com/events/fairs-festivals/bayfield-apple-festival-41264|accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> *Listed as one of the “10 Best Specialty Food Festivals in the Nation” by [[USA Today]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Travel Wisconsin|url=https://www.travelwisconsin.com/events/fairs-festivals/bayfield-apple-festival-41264|accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> *The [[Microbrewery|craft-brewed]] '''AppleFest Ale''' is a popular drink produced by the local [[South Shore Brewery]], and is seasonally available in the fall.<ref>{{cite web|title=Southshorebrewery.com|url=https://www.southshorebrewery.com/news/applefest-ale-2017-debut|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>
